230
00:16:58,870 --> 00:17:00,370
[SPEAKER_07]: So I'm just going to give you my thoughts.

231
00:17:01,411 --> 00:17:05,692
[SPEAKER_07]: First of all, I think that the public meeting was very successful.

232
00:17:06,072 --> 00:17:07,773
[SPEAKER_07]: I think that combined with

233
00:17:08,346 --> 00:17:11,689
[SPEAKER_07]: you know, looking for new members has really started a great conversation.

234
00:17:11,749 --> 00:17:14,071
[SPEAKER_07]: I've had a lot of good conversations about the charter.

235
00:17:14,832 --> 00:17:20,457
[SPEAKER_07]: I just want to, I just think we need to step back a little bit to talk about process.

236
00:17:21,978 --> 00:17:24,360
[SPEAKER_07]: So I have notes here, I'm just going to read to them.

237
00:17:24,661 --> 00:17:30,486
[SPEAKER_07]: On March 2nd, we voted to create a new charter, not change the existing charter, create a new charter.

238
00:17:33,043 --> 00:17:39,009
[SPEAKER_07]: My concern is that the charter, as the Collins folks will tell you, is a massive document.

239
00:17:39,689 --> 00:17:49,819
[SPEAKER_07]: It also is a document that if anybody's tried to find rules and regulations for school committee, they really don't exist in our Medford charter.

240
00:17:50,740 --> 00:17:54,844
[SPEAKER_07]: So in eight months of doing this, and I know we're all working extremely hard,

241
00:17:57,316 --> 00:18:05,487
[SPEAKER_07]: We're, we're kind of like we're kind of stuck on the obvious big issues that we're looking at the city council has made their three amendments known.

242
00:18:06,208 --> 00:18:10,674
[SPEAKER_07]: We've been talking, you know about, you know, leadership and the executive branch.

243
00:18:13,962 --> 00:18:22,444
[SPEAKER_07]: I think the one thing that we owe the public in the process and the legacy of what the charter is supposed to be is that we have a true process.

244
00:18:22,464 --> 00:18:32,406
[SPEAKER_07]: And to me, that process is about creating a document that citizens will be able to start their own process when they don't like something in the charter.

245
00:18:33,366 --> 00:18:39,207
[SPEAKER_07]: I think that that's an extremely important document because when we do this, and when it's on a ballot,

246
00:18:40,180 --> 00:18:43,282
[SPEAKER_07]: The way I envision it, the ballot's gonna have a charter.

247
00:18:43,642 --> 00:18:44,843
[SPEAKER_07]: Do you want the charter or not?

248
00:18:46,444 --> 00:19:00,692
[SPEAKER_07]: It's not necessarily, to me, in my mind, I think what we have to combine with the charter that we end up deciding on is we also need to give the citizens a process that if they see 90%, they like 90% of the charter on the day of election day,

249
00:19:03,906 --> 00:19:08,991
[SPEAKER_07]: they can vote for that charter and know that tomorrow they can fill out this form and start this process.

250
00:19:09,612 --> 00:19:15,918
[SPEAKER_07]: So I'm very much concerned about how this process goes and how we attack each issue.

251
00:19:15,938 --> 00:19:21,863
[SPEAKER_07]: Because if we're creating something new, we need to really get deep, deep down and figure that out.

252
00:19:22,304 --> 00:19:25,387
[SPEAKER_07]: So I'm suggesting tonight that we form two subcommittees.

253
00:19:27,263 --> 00:19:36,087
[SPEAKER_07]: One subcommittee is to work with the Collins Center to really research the details of the existing charter in combination with the Mass General Laws.

254
00:19:37,808 --> 00:19:47,573
[SPEAKER_07]: The second subcommittee would be to create that form of change where citizens can fill it out and, you know,

255
00:19:49,237 --> 00:19:58,681
[SPEAKER_07]: The next level of this is to form a permanent charter review board where you would come and you'd have that discussion and give you a platform after we're done.

256
00:19:58,781 --> 00:20:08,386
[SPEAKER_07]: It's not us, but maybe a seven panel group that would convene twice a year that you can fill out your form and have that discussion.

257
00:20:08,826 --> 00:20:14,608
[SPEAKER_07]: So I think the best gift we give to the city is to have a process in the future that allows us to make changes.

258
00:20:16,169 --> 00:20:17,490
[SPEAKER_07]: I think, you know,

259
00:20:18,678 --> 00:20:20,618
[SPEAKER_07]: believe me, I know how hard we're all working.

260
00:20:21,099 --> 00:20:30,961
[SPEAKER_07]: I think subcommittees may be the option that we can really start getting down and dirty in subcommittees and come up with a presentation to the committee of the whole that says two things.

261
00:20:32,341 --> 00:20:37,342
[SPEAKER_07]: This is the charter, take a look at it and make your changes because we have to vote on that.

262
00:20:37,942 --> 00:20:40,383
[SPEAKER_07]: And number two is to create an atmosphere for people

263
00:20:41,382 --> 00:20:50,784
[SPEAKER_07]: to be able to vote on this charter, knowing that 75% of the charter, they're like 25%, they don't, but I'm not gonna vote no on the charter because of that.

264
00:20:50,824 --> 00:20:59,266
[SPEAKER_07]: Because I also know that there's a process established by this committee that allows us to make changes much more frequently than every four decades.

265
00:20:59,746 --> 00:21:02,327
[SPEAKER_07]: So, those are my thoughts.

266
00:21:02,367 --> 00:21:11,149
[SPEAKER_07]: I think that when you look at the massive undertaking that we have, I think subcommittees are a great answer to get some of the grunt work done

267
00:21:11,849 --> 00:21:28,701
[SPEAKER_07]: And I think we somehow, and I'm not, this is just, you know, my thoughts as I stare out my window and look at the water, but it's extremely important that we leave behind a process that people have that say, I don't like the way this is done.

268
00:21:29,181 --> 00:21:30,142
[SPEAKER_07]: Well, here's the form.

269
00:21:30,182 --> 00:21:36,186
[SPEAKER_07]: You tell us what the charter law is now, what you want the change to be, and then it's a simple form.

270
00:21:36,766 --> 00:21:37,206
[SPEAKER_07]: What do you want?

271
00:21:37,266 --> 00:21:38,647
[SPEAKER_07]: What's the charter rule?

272
00:21:38,747 --> 00:21:40,228
[SPEAKER_07]: What's the law that you want to change?

273
00:21:40,289 --> 00:21:40,949
[SPEAKER_07]: What item number?

274
00:21:41,589 --> 00:21:45,531
[SPEAKER_07]: what's the change you want, and explain to us why you think that's an important change.

275
00:21:45,971 --> 00:21:57,177
[SPEAKER_07]: I've also commented too that, although we're just beginning our interview process, a lot of the interviews, if you read the interviews, are talking about the problems that the city has and something that they wanna see changed.

276
00:21:57,637 --> 00:22:01,199
[SPEAKER_07]: But there's very little in the interview that says, how about if we do it this way?

277
00:22:01,779 --> 00:22:10,404
[SPEAKER_07]: And so we have to start creating a base for people to not only just complain, because it's easy to find the problem, it's really hard to find the solution.

278
00:22:11,044 --> 00:22:11,924
[SPEAKER_07]: that interaction.

279
00:22:11,964 --> 00:22:13,365
[SPEAKER_07]: So those are my thoughts.

280
00:22:14,205 --> 00:22:22,008
[SPEAKER_07]: I wanted to be brief, but those are my thoughts, and I think we can have a real positive impact into the future of what the charter does.

