700
01:05:56,057 --> 01:06:01,660
[SPEAKER_05]: And there's a shortage and they're often far more expensive than a mayor.

701
01:06:01,800 --> 01:06:04,322
[SPEAKER_05]: And they kind of sold me on it being

702
01:06:06,914 --> 01:06:08,275
[SPEAKER_05]: not a very good idea.

703
01:06:08,375 --> 01:06:14,040
[SPEAKER_05]: And I just wanted to remind people of what they had said to us.

704
01:06:14,060 --> 01:06:15,561
[SPEAKER_05]: That's it.

705
01:06:15,581 --> 01:06:15,761
[SPEAKER_12]: Great.

706
01:06:16,422 --> 01:06:16,862
[SPEAKER_12]: Thank you.

707
01:06:17,703 --> 01:06:18,944
[SPEAKER_12]: John and then Danielle.

708
01:06:20,785 --> 01:06:21,686
[SPEAKER_00]: I have a few thoughts.

709
01:06:21,786 --> 01:06:23,548
[SPEAKER_00]: I agree with what was just said.

710
01:06:23,588 --> 01:06:24,789
[SPEAKER_00]: That was one of the things I want to bring up.

711
01:06:24,809 --> 01:06:25,289
[SPEAKER_00]: So thank you.

712
01:06:25,649 --> 01:06:27,351
[SPEAKER_00]: The other thing is I do like having a mayor.

713
01:06:27,631 --> 01:06:28,411
[SPEAKER_00]: I do think there's

714
01:06:30,157 --> 01:06:35,002
[SPEAKER_00]: community aspect to it that people like, you know, rallying around one person.

715
01:06:36,264 --> 01:06:39,166
[SPEAKER_00]: In terms of qualifications, people do hire staff.

716
01:06:40,988 --> 01:06:44,912
[SPEAKER_00]: So to the extent we're worried about that, I think it's manageable.

717
01:06:45,152 --> 01:06:47,315
[SPEAKER_00]: And as was just pointed out, city managers

718
01:06:48,743 --> 01:06:51,244
[SPEAKER_00]: It's not easy to hire one, so we might run into that problem anyway.

719
01:06:52,284 --> 01:06:57,706
[SPEAKER_00]: I think transition from current practice to now, it's worth keeping a mayor in mind.

720
01:06:58,126 --> 01:07:05,608
[SPEAKER_00]: If we're talking about something that people embrace and adopt, deviating too far from what we currently do might be a red flag.

721
01:07:06,229 --> 01:07:06,909
[SPEAKER_00]: Change is difficult.

722
01:07:08,009 --> 01:07:09,290
[SPEAKER_00]: And I had another point and I forget what it was.

723
01:07:09,550 --> 01:07:16,892
[SPEAKER_00]: Oh, I do think there's always a real inclination, I totally get it, to take politics out of government.

724
01:07:17,599 --> 01:07:23,243
[SPEAKER_00]: And I think when we think about what that means, we're thinking about sort of corruption favoritism, a hundred percent, we get that stuff out.

725
01:07:24,924 --> 01:07:28,527
[SPEAKER_00]: But, you know, deciding how to prioritize things, that's politics too.

726
01:07:28,707 --> 01:07:30,688
[SPEAKER_00]: And I think it's important to have those things.

727
01:07:30,969 --> 01:07:32,950
[SPEAKER_00]: And I think an elected mayor does that.

728
01:07:32,990 --> 01:07:38,534
[SPEAKER_00]: So I just say I like having elected mayor and those are my reasons.

729
01:07:39,275 --> 01:07:39,495
[SPEAKER_08]: Great.

730
01:07:39,815 --> 01:07:40,896
[SPEAKER_12]: Thank you, Danielle.

731
01:07:42,123 --> 01:07:45,004
[SPEAKER_08]: I won't talk for too long, because I just want to echo pretty much what John said.

732
01:07:45,024 --> 01:07:51,325
[SPEAKER_08]: I think the elected element of having a mayor and sort of a community-based position, I do appreciate.

733
01:07:51,345 --> 01:07:55,066
[SPEAKER_12]: Thanks.

734
01:07:55,346 --> 01:07:55,626
[SPEAKER_12]: Eunice?

735
01:07:58,227 --> 01:08:01,368
[SPEAKER_11]: I see pluses and minuses, definitely, to both.

736
01:08:02,488 --> 01:08:06,789
[SPEAKER_11]: I think my biggest concern, and I think I mentioned it when we hit on this months ago,

737
01:08:12,507 --> 01:08:22,537
[SPEAKER_11]: Mayor, the mayor gets elected, does the mayor actually have the skill set to run a multi-million dollar corporation, which is essentially what a city is.

738
01:08:23,918 --> 01:08:34,188
[SPEAKER_11]: But I think in reading through what you sent us, the part about, you know, I think it was Daniela, somebody mentioned, or John,

739
01:08:34,797 --> 01:08:57,872
[SPEAKER_11]: You know, they hire the department heads certainly that are allegedly skilled in their area of expertise, but also the point of hiring a chief administrative officer to balance any shortcomings that the mayor might have, I think is key.

740
01:08:58,472 --> 01:09:01,034
[SPEAKER_11]: And I think that kind of

741
01:09:01,863 --> 01:09:09,065
[SPEAKER_11]: offsets the idea that a city manager would come in with allegedly the skillset to manage a city.

742
01:09:09,526 --> 01:09:17,108
[SPEAKER_11]: But if you have the mayor and then a chief administrative officer, or maybe the chief of staff that we have now, or something like that.

743
01:09:17,548 --> 01:09:24,851
[SPEAKER_11]: But I also think that we need to be, and we'll get into this with the interviews, is the idea of what

744
01:09:29,715 --> 01:09:52,552
[SPEAKER_11]: piece, what, what form of government works best for Medford, based upon, and I think, you know, based upon some of the interviews that have been held already, especially those of the staff in the executive office, what, given where we are now with

745
01:09:53,360 --> 01:10:00,365
[SPEAKER_11]: the issues and problems that we face, which largely stem from having had a mayor for 30 years.

746
01:10:03,867 --> 01:10:13,334
[SPEAKER_11]: We need to pay attention to the fact that we need to consider a form of government where we're not in that predicament again.

747
01:10:13,354 --> 01:10:18,737
[SPEAKER_11]: I suppose term limits could probably take care of that in one fell swoop.

748
01:10:19,278 --> 01:10:21,339
[SPEAKER_11]: But I think we need to be listening closely to

749
01:10:22,685 --> 01:10:33,449
[SPEAKER_11]: you know, what our current executive branches is saying about the issues and challenges they're facing in terms of what might work best for the city.

750
01:10:35,550 --> 01:10:35,890
[SPEAKER_12]: Thanks.

751
01:10:37,571 --> 01:10:38,151
[SPEAKER_12]: Anybody else?

752
01:10:38,531 --> 01:10:38,831
[SPEAKER_12]: Jean?

753
01:10:42,513 --> 01:10:48,215
[SPEAKER_10]: I am personally more in favor of mayor versus city manager.

754
01:10:49,652 --> 01:11:05,505
[SPEAKER_10]: Given personal experience I had when I worked at the state and gave significant funding to a city that had a city manager and found it, I think the argument for city manager is that it takes it out of politics.

755
01:11:06,186 --> 01:11:12,991
[SPEAKER_10]: My experience was that the city manager was responsive to a city council that was very divided.

756
01:11:14,136 --> 01:11:25,002
[SPEAKER_10]: and the staff and the city that were running the program that we were funding felt unsupported by the city manager who was trying to manage the divided city council.

757
01:11:25,983 --> 01:11:31,446
[SPEAKER_10]: And so it didn't seem more effective to me, but that was one city.

758
01:11:33,227 --> 01:11:42,932
[SPEAKER_10]: At the same time, I think one of the biggest comments we've gotten from people that we've heard from so far is that they feel like the balance of power is not

759
01:11:44,342 --> 01:11:47,465
[SPEAKER_10]: that there isn't a good balance of power in the city.

760
01:11:49,006 --> 01:11:59,353
[SPEAKER_10]: And that is one way to address the balance of power is to have a city manager who's responsive to city council.

761
01:11:59,914 --> 01:12:10,001
[SPEAKER_10]: There are other ways to balance power in the city that if we don't go in the direction of the city manager, I think we should explore other ways

762
01:12:12,123 --> 01:12:14,165
[SPEAKER_10]: You mentioned term limits might be one.

763
01:12:14,725 --> 01:12:24,752
[SPEAKER_10]: There are other options to have more of a balance of power that we should consider but city manager might address some of the concerns from residents.

764
01:12:25,173 --> 01:12:27,555
[SPEAKER_10]: It's just my experience is it didn't really

765
01:12:28,495 --> 01:12:30,236
[SPEAKER_10]: make city government more effective.

766
01:12:31,156 --> 01:12:34,777
[SPEAKER_10]: That would be my worry, especially if your city council is very divided.

767
01:12:36,697 --> 01:12:44,199
[SPEAKER_10]: City manager may not really know how to respond to divided city council in a way to run programs.

768
01:12:45,179 --> 01:12:46,340
[SPEAKER_10]: But that was just one city.

769
01:12:46,360 --> 01:12:55,102
[SPEAKER_10]: I did research Arlington, Amherst, a lot of places do have city managers, and I don't know that they're not being effective.

770
01:12:55,893 --> 01:13:03,976
[SPEAKER_10]: And I'd be very curious to know why it seemed like people were very unhappy with Medford when it had a city manager, and that's why we went to the strong mayor.

771
01:13:04,436 --> 01:13:09,898
[SPEAKER_10]: And I don't, like the articles you sent didn't really say what the issues were and why we switched.

772
01:13:10,679 --> 01:13:14,820
[SPEAKER_10]: And it'd be good to know what the history is on that, if anybody here knows.

773
01:13:17,601 --> 01:13:19,582
[SPEAKER_12]: Maybe somebody does, but Ron, let me hear from you.

774
01:13:20,717 --> 01:13:32,839
[SPEAKER_07]: Yeah, just quickly, I'm prepared to vote on whether we go manager or mayor, but I also, you know, there are so many subsets to this that we can, like Jean says, redefine that position.

775
01:13:33,260 --> 01:13:38,921
[SPEAKER_07]: But, you know, as far as, you know, I think we've, I think we've had a lot of input as to understanding it.

776
01:13:38,941 --> 01:13:45,162
[SPEAKER_07]: And I think there's a lot of tweaking we can do in term limits and powers and whatnot, but mayor versus

777
01:13:46,075 --> 01:13:49,518
[SPEAKER_07]: city manager seems, for me personally, is a cut and dry.

778
01:13:49,538 --> 01:13:57,784
[SPEAKER_07]: I'm voting mayor through this whole process, and I would like to get into the more details of defining those roles and powers.

779
01:13:58,825 --> 01:13:59,865
[SPEAKER_12]: Okay, thanks.

780
01:14:03,088 --> 01:14:13,455
[SPEAKER_12]: So we've heard from a lot of people, and I'm hearing sort of an overwhelming sense in the committee right now that mayor is the way to stay.

781
01:14:14,990 --> 01:14:35,581
[SPEAKER_12]: I just wanted to reflect back on a point that John made that I think is really important, not just for this discussion, but for all the discussions we'll be having, which is that, you know, we, the reason we decided to create a new charter is because the charter is almost non-existent.

782
01:14:35,621 --> 01:14:43,225
[SPEAKER_12]: It's a two pages and it interacts with all these state laws and special acts, but at the same time,

783
01:14:44,880 --> 01:14:53,402
[SPEAKER_12]: Um, having a ton of change might, might be hard, might be hard for, um, for us to get, get through.

784
01:14:53,522 --> 01:15:06,704
[SPEAKER_12]: So, and this is just kind of the first example of, um, a major issue that we faced that if, if, if there was, um, a feeling among the committee that, oh, maybe we should switch to city manager, that would be a major change.

785
01:15:07,384 --> 01:15:08,584
[SPEAKER_12]: Um, I'm not hearing it.

786
01:15:08,884 --> 01:15:11,385
[SPEAKER_12]: So, um, I think.

787
01:15:12,595 --> 01:15:18,658
[SPEAKER_12]: I don't know, I mean, I think if we do vote tonight, I mean, I think it would, it will just need to be a tentative vote.

788
01:15:18,718 --> 01:15:25,200
[SPEAKER_12]: I'm also hearing that there's a lot of pieces that are gonna interact with this decision while there's a strong preference to maybe stay with mayor.

789
01:15:26,301 --> 01:15:37,325
[SPEAKER_12]: There's also a lot of details around that, like balance of power, like avoiding an entrenched situation that would be addressed down the line for sure.

790
01:15:38,406 --> 01:15:39,507
[SPEAKER_12]: in our future discussions.

791
01:15:40,167 --> 01:15:51,313
[SPEAKER_12]: So, and we also clearly, if we did a survey and we found out that like a thousand people answered the survey and 90% of them said city manager, then we can always come back and revisit it.

792
01:15:52,854 --> 01:15:57,817
[SPEAKER_12]: But not sure that that will happen, but we can leave ourselves open to that.

793
01:15:57,897 --> 01:16:06,862
[SPEAKER_12]: So if we did vote, I think I would suggest that it would be a sort of a tentative decision, but it would be a good step in the right direction of,

794
01:16:07,728 --> 01:16:11,570
[SPEAKER_12]: being able to get into some of those other issues that have come up in this discussion.

795
01:16:15,951 --> 01:16:18,552
[SPEAKER_11]: So, yeah, I think you're right, Melva.

796
01:16:18,572 --> 01:16:30,377
[SPEAKER_11]: I think, you know, we need, we're at a stalemate if we don't know which way we're going to go in terms of everything else that we have to do.

797
01:16:30,979 --> 01:16:33,020
[SPEAKER_11]: because each path is a bit different.

798
01:16:34,481 --> 01:16:36,402
[SPEAKER_11]: But again, I think you're right.

799
01:16:36,422 --> 01:16:58,693
[SPEAKER_11]: I mean, we have to open ourselves up to, you know, there's a sector of the city that has experienced both forms of government, but I think there's a larger swath of the city at this point that has only experienced the mayor council form of government.

800
01:16:59,606 --> 01:17:22,505
[SPEAKER_11]: But I think we have to be prepared for the fact that maybe after people, you know, some surveys go out, we do some focus groups and other things and people learn about the two different types that, you know, maybe, maybe the city will surprise us and, you know, we'll have, you know, 90% of the people telling us we need to go in a different direction.

801
01:17:23,045 --> 01:17:23,966
[SPEAKER_11]: Yeah, we have to.

802
01:17:25,171 --> 01:17:26,051
[SPEAKER_11]: do something now.

803
01:17:27,212 --> 01:17:30,093
[SPEAKER_11]: And I just like to sit here or we go one way or the other.

804
01:17:30,513 --> 01:17:31,014
[SPEAKER_11]: Yeah.

805
01:17:31,034 --> 01:17:31,894
[SPEAKER_12]: Anthony, was that you?

806
01:17:32,554 --> 01:17:37,816
[SPEAKER_05]: I just like to say I'm old enough to remember the the city manager.

807
01:17:37,856 --> 01:17:38,297
[SPEAKER_05]: Yeah.

808
01:17:38,357 --> 01:17:48,341
[SPEAKER_05]: And, and, you know, if you think there's a lot of dysfunction, and, and, you know, the, I won't even say what, what branch of

809
01:17:48,928 --> 01:17:51,390
[SPEAKER_05]: government, it was worse.

810
01:17:51,970 --> 01:18:01,737
[SPEAKER_05]: And there was a lot of opportunity for nepotism and different forms of minor corruption in the city.

811
01:18:01,837 --> 01:18:06,240
[SPEAKER_05]: And the city manager was beholden to the city council.

812
01:18:06,300 --> 01:18:09,282
[SPEAKER_05]: And it really wasn't good.

813
01:18:09,342 --> 01:18:15,107
[SPEAKER_05]: And a lot of the city managers also at the time that they were planning on building the

814
01:18:16,312 --> 01:18:20,534
[SPEAKER_05]: old high school, which was the new high school when I was coming up.

815
01:18:21,934 --> 01:18:45,985
[SPEAKER_05]: I'd like to just put it in the form of a motion that we table the discussion about sitting manager until we are motivated by the public to re-engage with it and kind of not like have a tentative vote on

816
01:18:46,475 --> 01:18:55,441
[SPEAKER_05]: continuing to explore, uh, you know, the role of the mayor, but not a city manager, unless people, uh, you know, kind of compel us to do that.

817
01:18:55,901 --> 01:18:56,301
[SPEAKER_05]: Okay.

818
01:18:57,402 --> 01:18:58,162
[SPEAKER_12]: Um, okay.

819
01:18:58,323 --> 01:19:00,964
[SPEAKER_12]: So, um, that, thank you for that motion.

820
01:19:00,984 --> 01:19:03,706
[SPEAKER_12]: Um, I just want to hear from Maury before we get, look for it.

821
01:19:03,766 --> 01:19:04,266
[SPEAKER_01]: So I'm sorry.

822
01:19:04,286 --> 01:19:04,807
[SPEAKER_01]: That's okay.

823
01:19:06,069 --> 01:19:07,130
[SPEAKER_01]: That's quite all right, Anthony.

824
01:19:07,150 --> 01:19:08,051
[SPEAKER_01]: Thank you.

825
01:19:08,631 --> 01:19:14,075
[SPEAKER_01]: As Anthony has, I lived through both forms of government here for years.

826
01:19:14,176 --> 01:19:16,637
[SPEAKER_01]: And I'm going to reiterate what Anthony said there.

827
01:19:17,078 --> 01:19:23,263
[SPEAKER_01]: The city manager, he answered to the city council, because the city council elected him.

828
01:19:23,823 --> 01:19:28,767
[SPEAKER_01]: Whatever they wanted, the majority, four out of seven, wanted that.

829
01:19:28,827 --> 01:19:29,788
[SPEAKER_01]: That's how it went.

830
01:19:31,789 --> 01:19:39,973
[SPEAKER_01]: And it was like the old boy club, let's whip them on Tuesday night and then all go out and have dinner and drinks afterwards.

831
01:19:40,093 --> 01:19:44,936
[SPEAKER_01]: And it was strictly as the strong survived.

832
01:19:45,636 --> 01:19:54,461
[SPEAKER_01]: This way, and you had nobody that's totally accountable because you couldn't, the public had no input in electing the person who was running the city.

833
01:19:55,366 --> 01:20:18,606
[SPEAKER_01]: You know, this way, the accountability is there, whether it's two years, three years, four year terms of the mayor, but certainly if the public and the community doesn't go along with the way the direction the city is going in, you can go to the polls and you can voice your opinion, where you have no say in a city manager type government.

834
01:20:20,928 --> 01:20:21,709
[SPEAKER_12]: Great, thanks.

835
01:20:22,665 --> 01:20:37,128
[SPEAKER_12]: Okay, so I just wanna say what I understand the motion to be by Anthony, that we continue deliberations on mayor as executive branch and table discussion of city manager unless public data steers us back to it.

836
01:20:41,108 --> 01:20:41,748
[SPEAKER_12]: Does somebody?

837
01:20:42,768 --> 01:20:43,689
[SPEAKER_03]: I second it.

838
01:20:44,449 --> 01:20:46,889
[SPEAKER_03]: I'll second, yeah, okay.

839
01:20:47,169 --> 01:20:48,649
[SPEAKER_12]: And are we all in favor?

840
01:20:49,410 --> 01:20:49,530
[SPEAKER_12]: Aye.

841
01:20:50,050 --> 01:20:50,330
[SPEAKER_03]: Aye.

842
01:20:50,510 --> 01:20:50,670
[SPEAKER_03]: Aye.

843
01:20:51,110 --> 01:20:51,210
[SPEAKER_12]: Aye.

844
01:20:52,832 --> 01:20:55,573
[SPEAKER_12]: Great work, so we made a big step forward, I think.

845
01:20:56,074 --> 01:20:56,614
[SPEAKER_02]: Yay!

846
01:20:58,875 --> 01:21:00,816
[SPEAKER_12]: Okay, so interviews.

847
01:21:03,577 --> 01:21:05,498
[SPEAKER_12]: Have I shared the folder with everybody?

848
