[SPEAKER_12]: And it looks like we have Matt, right?

1241
01:52:27,118 --> 01:52:29,040
[SPEAKER_12]: MP, yeah.

1242
01:52:31,142 --> 01:52:31,342
[SPEAKER_12]: Great.

1243
01:52:31,362 --> 01:52:31,883
[SPEAKER_06]: Okay, very good.

1244
01:52:31,923 --> 01:52:39,571
[SPEAKER_06]: Yeah, so I finally have three minutes, but I have three topics to hit up, and I'm really glad that you all have decided to kind of change this around in the future.

1245
01:52:39,591 --> 01:52:42,354
[SPEAKER_06]: Perhaps people like myself will be able to talk during the meetings.

1246
01:52:43,244 --> 01:52:45,707
[SPEAKER_06]: But anyway, I mean, I kind of watch this meeting.

1247
01:52:45,827 --> 01:52:49,130
[SPEAKER_06]: I've been considered previously if I should like apply to this meeting.

1248
01:52:49,691 --> 01:52:57,880
[SPEAKER_06]: And I kind of, you know, I see some kind of things that like, you know, like I was saying in the chat, you know, two thirds of the meeting in, the committee was stuck on the fifth element out of 12.

1249
01:52:58,360 --> 01:53:01,944
[SPEAKER_06]: And that's basically, that's I think a situation people generally kind of want to avoid.

1250
01:53:02,344 --> 01:53:04,206
[SPEAKER_06]: I know that sometimes when I'm like,

1251
01:53:05,227 --> 01:53:06,609
[SPEAKER_06]: creating agendas and stuff like that.

1252
01:53:06,629 --> 01:53:10,752
[SPEAKER_06]: I'll ask for people to think about certain things that will be discussed and take notes before showing up.

1253
01:53:11,433 --> 01:53:13,955
[SPEAKER_06]: Sometimes that can make the meeting a little bit more efficient.

1254
01:53:14,276 --> 01:53:25,806
[SPEAKER_06]: But I really wanted to raise my hand or whatever and support what Anthony said, because this question of asking for people's age is, I think, Anthony said something that was really important.

1255
01:53:25,826 --> 01:53:28,509
[SPEAKER_06]: I don't know if everybody really kind of registered with everybody's

1256
01:53:29,149 --> 01:53:31,631
[SPEAKER_06]: trying to figure out what exactly is the data that you want.

1257
01:53:32,272 --> 01:53:38,357
[SPEAKER_06]: You really have to know why do you want that data because you really have to ask, what is the point of getting everybody's age?

1258
01:53:38,398 --> 01:53:40,359
[SPEAKER_06]: It might be a nice little thing to have.

1259
01:53:40,399 --> 01:53:45,064
[SPEAKER_06]: People are curious what older folks or longer living people here have to say rather than younger people.

1260
01:53:45,364 --> 01:53:51,009
[SPEAKER_06]: But the question is, is that just something interesting or that's really data that's going to be useful as far as changing this charter?

1261
01:53:51,369 --> 01:53:53,952
[SPEAKER_06]: Because if you really do all that age stuff,

1262
01:53:54,452 --> 01:53:59,038
[SPEAKER_06]: then you're really kind of taking on another role of trying to figure out if you're sampling correctly.

1263
01:53:59,498 --> 01:54:10,131
[SPEAKER_06]: My guess is that by putting in these questions like age just because of curiosity, but not because they're necessary, would wind up revealing that certain groups were oversampled.

1264
01:54:10,932 --> 01:54:18,097
[SPEAKER_06]: And then you would have to have this other issue of how do we make sure that we do all of like proportional sampling to the different populations in the city.

1265
01:54:18,357 --> 01:54:22,100
[SPEAKER_06]: And there's many, many different populations in the city, depending on how you break them all up.

1266
01:54:23,100 --> 01:54:28,564
[SPEAKER_06]: So, I mean, I think like that is basically, that's a job for people that are like serious data analysts.

1267
01:54:29,005 --> 01:54:33,908
[SPEAKER_06]: And that's a job where you can probably get a lot of information from City Hall about how they try to do a better job.

1268
01:54:34,348 --> 01:54:36,170
[SPEAKER_06]: for sampling certain populations.

1269
01:54:36,631 --> 01:54:42,337
[SPEAKER_06]: But yeah, I really think that the group should kind of figure out what is the data we actually need to figure out how to create the right charter.

1270
01:54:42,697 --> 01:54:49,585
[SPEAKER_06]: And that should be focused on, because I know when I'm filling out surveys, and I know a lot of people who are filling out surveys, every single one of these little questions can get really annoying.

1271
01:54:49,905 --> 01:54:51,807
[SPEAKER_06]: When I'm like, how many more questions are going to be?

1272
01:54:51,847 --> 01:54:55,071
[SPEAKER_06]: They want my age, they want to know my neighborhood, they want to know how long I've lived here.

1273
01:54:55,411 --> 01:55:08,920
[SPEAKER_06]: You know, it can just wind up frustrating people and you could wind up seeing a smaller retention rate, as far as how many people fill out the whole survey, but you know I have two other items that I've already spoke for probably more than three minutes I'll probably just keep it at that.

1274
01:55:09,981 --> 01:55:11,021
[SPEAKER_12]: No, you can keep speaking.

1275
01:55:11,281 --> 01:55:11,902
[SPEAKER_06]: Okay, well then.

1276
01:55:12,222 --> 01:55:13,343
[SPEAKER_06]: Okay, so the second item is.

1277
01:55:14,740 --> 01:55:17,361
[SPEAKER_06]: It's some things are not clear to me when I watch these meetings.

1278
01:55:17,981 --> 01:55:33,907
[SPEAKER_06]: And one of them is how much of the input can the actual members have versus the public now, my understanding is this committee has a responsibility of coming up with some recommendations and then bring them forth the city and the public will vote on them, but there seems to be some times when the committee is actually.

1279
01:55:34,787 --> 01:55:41,170
[SPEAKER_06]: almost, I don't know if this is fair, but kind of putting the thumb on the scales being that myself as a committee member, I want a mayor.

1280
01:55:41,510 --> 01:55:44,071
[SPEAKER_06]: I don't want to, because I remember how bad it used to be a long time ago.

1281
01:55:45,132 --> 01:55:53,275
[SPEAKER_06]: And it's really, it's kind of concerning to me if people, I know like a few months back, there was this discussion about change the whole charter or just amend it.

1282
01:55:53,395 --> 01:55:56,316
[SPEAKER_06]: And the majority said, let's just change the whole thing.

1283
01:55:56,597 --> 01:56:04,280
[SPEAKER_06]: But it seems to me like this may be a little bit premature if you're still kind of working on surveys of asking the public what they want and we haven't to the focus groups yet.

1284
01:56:04,700 --> 01:56:15,533
[SPEAKER_06]: should this committee be kind of voting on, well, I've got a soft spot for McMayor Coke rather than, you know, make City Manager Pepsi before the public has really, really, really been heard from comprehensively.

1285
01:56:15,573 --> 01:56:24,264
[SPEAKER_06]: I think that's something to kind of consider as a group kind of comes up with an understanding of how do we, how does the group kind of come up with its recommendations.

1286
01:56:24,824 --> 01:56:39,350
[SPEAKER_06]: Is it really really based on the city, the populace, is it more based on what people internally kind of have prerogatives for, or is it like it seems like the group is going to have to continue to kind of try to negotiate, you know how much impact the personal preferences the committee members have.

1287
01:56:40,030 --> 01:56:48,932
[SPEAKER_06]: and the public by and large, when the group has already understood that many people in the population really haven't even grokked these concepts yet, the possibilities.

1288
01:56:49,032 --> 01:56:50,673
[SPEAKER_06]: So it does seem premature about that.

1289
01:56:50,693 --> 01:56:54,834
[SPEAKER_06]: But my last thing, I think my camera just went out.

1290
01:56:56,594 --> 01:56:57,754
[SPEAKER_06]: My computer just went off.

1291
01:56:58,074 --> 01:56:58,354
[SPEAKER_06]: Hold on.

1292
01:57:00,035 --> 01:57:04,056
[SPEAKER_06]: Well, my computer went to sleep, so if y'all can wait.

1293
01:57:05,996 --> 01:57:07,957
[SPEAKER_06]: Anyway, I can continue to talk.

1294
01:57:09,568 --> 01:57:10,849
[SPEAKER_06]: I don't know, can you hear me?

1295
01:57:10,869 --> 01:57:11,589
[SPEAKER_12]: Yeah.

1296
01:57:11,609 --> 01:57:14,551
[SPEAKER_12]: If you want to just make your final point, go ahead.

1297
01:57:14,791 --> 01:57:28,638
[SPEAKER_06]: So this whole thing about the mayor versus the city manager, this is a particular issue when if you have people in the particular committee who were saying, I have a soft spot for a McMayor rather than a McPepsi city manager.

1298
01:57:29,058 --> 01:57:35,221
[SPEAKER_06]: And they say, well, I remember, you know, 40 years ago, what it was like, or I've been to some place and it wasn't all it's cracked up to be.

1299
01:57:35,861 --> 01:57:38,482
[SPEAKER_06]: And I start to think, well, there's trade-offs with everything.

1300
01:57:38,883 --> 01:57:40,603
[SPEAKER_06]: There's trade-offs with having a city manager.

1301
01:57:41,023 --> 01:57:42,404
[SPEAKER_06]: There's trade-offs with having a mayor.

1302
01:57:42,484 --> 01:57:51,188
[SPEAKER_06]: And a lot of times when groups are coming through this process, they kind of have to figure out, and the public too, what are the trade-offs that we can live with?

1303
01:57:51,208 --> 01:58:00,472
[SPEAKER_06]: Because people can say things like, Maury said something that at least you have a say over the mayor, but you don't have a direct say over the city manager.

1304
01:58:00,912 --> 01:58:03,935
[SPEAKER_06]: Well, I mean, I think I have something to say that I think a lot of us can agree with.

1305
01:58:04,336 --> 01:58:11,603
[SPEAKER_06]: Down at City Hall, you don't have that direct say over every single person there except for the mayor, all the department heads.

1306
01:58:11,964 --> 01:58:12,784
[SPEAKER_06]: That's indirect.

1307
01:58:13,205 --> 01:58:15,787
[SPEAKER_06]: You know, all the staffers on the departments, that's indirect.

1308
01:58:16,048 --> 01:58:17,810
[SPEAKER_06]: These are people that are part of the bureaucracy.

1309
01:58:17,950 --> 01:58:21,333
[SPEAKER_06]: And thankfully, thankfully, these people are making the city run.

1310
01:58:22,309 --> 01:58:30,275
[SPEAKER_06]: these people that are in the bureaucracy, independently of which way the public swings because we're so angry at McMay or Koch this year.

1311
01:58:30,915 --> 01:58:32,837
[SPEAKER_06]: That's something really, really to consider.

1312
01:58:32,877 --> 01:58:47,908
[SPEAKER_06]: And I think that when we say, well, I remember all the bad things about the city manager, or I remember when the Collins Center said this is the drawback of the city manager, I think like we're only, you know, this discussion could be richer if instead of saying, well, I remember the bad things about the city manager,

1313
01:58:48,668 --> 01:58:53,534
[SPEAKER_06]: The commission, or the committee rather, would go around and take a look at different cities.

1314
01:58:53,914 --> 01:58:56,037
[SPEAKER_06]: How does the city manager work for them versus the mayor?

1315
01:58:56,077 --> 01:58:57,899
[SPEAKER_06]: What are the drawbacks they have and what are the benefits?

1316
01:58:58,320 --> 01:59:06,870
[SPEAKER_06]: That's the kind of process I think that a lot of times committees should be engaged in, rather than just kind of a personal appeals of, well, I prefer a place with the mayor.

1317
01:59:07,871 --> 01:59:22,960
[SPEAKER_06]: because it might just be at the end of all of this process that this whole community decides, you know, what we have right now, this is actually working a lot better and we're afraid of all the unintended consequences that could happen if we change it.

1318
01:59:23,280 --> 01:59:30,705
[SPEAKER_06]: I mean, that's really something to be open to is that we might just say, the public might just say no, just like they did like a couple of decades ago.

1319
01:59:31,085 --> 01:59:35,388
[SPEAKER_06]: But anyway, I'm glad you all listened in and these are just some things to reflect on.

1320
01:59:35,408 --> 01:59:35,728
[SPEAKER_06]: Thank you.

1321
01:59:36,820 --> 01:59:38,760
[SPEAKER_12]: Thank you so much for your feedback.

1322
01:59:40,581 --> 01:59:41,601
[SPEAKER_12]: And we hope you return.

1323
01:59:43,421 --> 01:59:48,042
[SPEAKER_12]: Okay, any final details?

1324
01:59:48,082 --> 01:59:51,163
[SPEAKER_12]: I think we're ready to close up where it's exactly 8.30.

1325
01:59:51,563 --> 01:59:56,463
[SPEAKER_12]: The meeting was actually, we lengthened the meeting to two hours this time.

1326
01:59:56,523 --> 02:00:02,264
[SPEAKER_12]: So we actually are right on the dot, which I'm very impressed by.

1327
02:00:02,284 --> 02:00:03,705
[SPEAKER_01]: I'll make a motion to adjourn.

1328
02:00:03,725 --> 02:00:04,645
[SPEAKER_12]: Thank you, Mark.

1329
02:00:04,725 --> 02:00:05,105
[SPEAKER_01]: Second.

1330
02:00:05,997 --> 02:00:07,141
[SPEAKER_12]: Great, all in favor.

1331
02:00:07,161 --> 02:00:07,221
[SPEAKER_12]: Aye.

1332
02:00:08,224 --> 02:00:08,325
[SPEAKER_01]: Aye.

1333
02:00:08,345 --> 02:00:08,405
[SPEAKER_01]: Aye.

1334
02:00:08,846 --> 02:00:09,127
[SPEAKER_12]: Aye.

1335
02:00:09,629 --> 02:00:09,810
[SPEAKER_12]: Aye.

1336
02:00:09,850 --> 02:00:10,050
[SPEAKER_12]: Aye.

